metadata.name: Caterpillars #85
metadata.description:
DISCLAIMER : 
I have started coding about 4 months ago and I am not very good at this. I have tried to clean up the code as best as I could, and I hope that there is nothing terribly wrong left inside. 

This will be kind of a charity project where the PRIMARY SALES will be 
divided as follows:
 - 60 % of primary sales will go to "Askida Fatura" -> https://askidafatura.ibb.gov.tr/
 - 20 % will go to Processing Foundation -> https://processingfoundation.org/
 - 20 % will go to Coding Train -> https://twitter.com/thecodingtrain

"Askida Fatura" is run by Istanbul Municipality and is a campaign that is used for paying the utility bills of the less fortunate living in Istanbul. On average, a couple of tezos pays one bill, and I hope to pay 5 - 10 bills with this.

I will figure out the best way to transfer the amounts later this week and the upcoming weeks, and will provide proof of transfer via my twitter. 

SINCE THIS IS CHARITY, I WILL NOT BE BURNING THE REMAINING EDITIONS!!!

Still, if you dont like what you got ping me and you can get your refund. 

twitter : https://twitter.com/evilnft
fxhash : https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/evilnft
objkt : https://objkt.com/profile/evilnft/created

about Caterpillars,

This is a humble project, does not try to achieve too much, and also wants you to not expect too much from it. 

features : 
 - 8 palettes
 - 2 different origins
 - 5 different characters
 - 6 to 49 sections
 - should be responsive, although I have only tested this on computers...

 press "s" to save a png.

metadata.name: Coloring With Lines #476
metadata.description:
This project started as a way to teach myself more about classes in p5.js by trying to code the "Chaos Game" method of plotting a Serpinski Triangle

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbKtFN71Lfs

Once figured out, I expanded the method to other shapes to see if different types of fractals might form. They did not, but the result was a series of points that could be connected with thin lines to draw shapes without using the native functions of p5. After working on colors it seemed like a nice enough project to release for free to everyone. Thank you all for your interest and support, hope you get a cool one!

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #64
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #178
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

metadata.name: Mooving Squigly #127
metadata.description:
A mooving squigly generator inspirated by "Chromie Squiggle by snowfro"
@ArtOnBlockchain on twitter
Made using p5.js

This project aim to be your unique mooving web3 signature

The features define the visual of your squigly
DIFFERENT FEATURES :

    Background Color: #7AA5A6, #FBB900, #FCBF49, #FFFFFF, #F5F3EC, #1F1F1F, #F9EBDC, #F0C328, #8AC1CC
    Squigly Color Theme: flash, chromatic, cloud, kaki, darkred
    Stroke: none, max 10
    Squigly Number: 1, 2, 3
    Special Color Mode: true, false
    Squigly Size: medium, small, large, extra large
    Speed: max 5
    Style: classic, expansion, distortion, blur, gray

The colours and positions are calculated using deterministic perlin noise
Press S to save the squigly
Reload the page to see your squigly moove again

Made with <3 by 0xtedy.tez / @0xtedy
All the code is opensource !
MIT License
